[src:jquery/ajax-programming] Ajax is not a technology, but rather a programming pattern.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] HTML and CSS can be used in combination to mark up and style information.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] The webpage can be modified by JavaScript to dynamically display (and allow the user to interact with) the new information.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] The built-in XMLHttpRequest object is used to execute Ajax on webpages, allowing websites to load content onto the screen without refreshing the page.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] In the early-to-mid 1990s, most websites were based on complete HTML pages.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] Each user action required a complete new page to be loaded from the server.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] This process was inefficient, as reflected by the user experience: all page content disappeared, then the new page appeared.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] Each time the browser reloaded a page because of a partial change, all the content had to be re-sent, even though only some of the information had changed.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] This placed additional load on the server and made bandwidth a limiting factor in performance.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] The foundations of AJAX originate back in 1996 with the introduction of JavaScript 1.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] Developers quickly discovered that any HTML element which accepted a "src" attribute could be used to fetch remote data.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] By changing the src of a hidden frame, a developer could fetch remote data, process or display it without a page refresh.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] The remote data could be a string, JavaScript code, XML or a partial HTML page generated on the server.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] The same could be done with `<img>` and `<embed>` tags, but many developers were alarmed at the concept of an executable GIF and preferred to use the hidden `<iframe>`.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] This technique was used for both Netscape Navigator and Internet Explorer, the two main browsers at the time, until developers discovered the XMLHTTP server object (MSXML 1.0) was included in Internet Explorer 4.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] Browser detection was then used to either implement the hidden `<iframe>` in Netscape or use the XMLHTTP (MSXML 1.0) object in IE 4.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] In 1996, the iframe tag was introduced by Internet Explorer; like the object element, it can load a part of the web page asynchronously.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] In 1998, the Microsoft Outlook Web Access team developed the concept behind the XMLHttpRequest scripting object.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] It appeared as XMLHTTP in the second version of the MSXML library, which shipped with Internet Explorer 5.0 in March 1999.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] The functionality of the Windows XMLHTTP ActiveX control in IE 5 was later implemented by Mozilla Firefox, Safari, Opera, Google Chrome, and other browsers as the XMLHttpRequest JavaScript object.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] Microsoft adopted the native XMLHttpRequest model as of Internet Explorer 7.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] Support for the ActiveX version remained in Internet Explorer and on "Internet Explorer mode" in Microsoft Edge.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] The utility of these background HTTP requests and asynchronous Web technologies remained fairly obscure until it started appearing in large scale online applications such as Outlook Web Access (2000) and Oddpost (2002).
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] Google made a wide deployment of standards-compliant, cross browser Ajax with Gmail (2004) and Google Maps (2005).
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] In October 2004 Kayak.com's public beta release was among the first large-scale e-commerce uses of what their developers at that time called "the xml http thing".
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] This increased interest in Ajax among web program developers.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] The term *AJAX* was publicly used on 18 February 2005 by Jesse James Garrett in an article titled *Ajax: A New Approach to Web Applications*, based on techniques used on Google pages.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] On 5 April 2006, the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) released the first draft specification for the XMLHttpRequest object in an attempt to create an official Web standard.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] The latest draft of the XMLHttpRequest object was published on 6 October 2016, and the XMLHttpRequest specification is now a living standard.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] The term *Ajax* has come to represent a broad group of Web technologies that can be used to implement a Web application that communicates with a server in the background, without interfering with the current state of the page.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] Since then, however, there have been a number of developments in the technologies used in an Ajax application, and in the definition of the term Ajax itself.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] XML is no longer required for data interchange and, therefore, XSLT is no longer required for the manipulation of data.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] JavaScript Object Notation (JSON) is often used as an alternative format for data interchange, although other formats such as preformatted HTML or plain text can also be used.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] A variety of popular JavaScript libraries, including jQuery, include abstractions to assist in executing Ajax requests.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] An example of a simple Ajax request using the GET method, written in JavaScript.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] Ajax offers several benefits that can significantly enhance web application performance and user experience.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] By reducing server traffic and improving speed, Ajax plays a crucial role in modern web development.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] One key advantage of Ajax is its capacity to render web applications without requiring data retrieval, resulting in reduced server traffic.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] This optimization minimizes response times on both the server and client sides, eliminating the need for users to endure loading screens.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] Furthermore, Ajax facilitates asynchronous processing by simplifying the utilization of XmlHttpRequest, which enables efficient handling of requests for asynchronous data retrieval.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] Additionally, the dynamic loading of content enhances the application's performance significantly.
[src:jquery/ajax-programming] Besides, Ajax enjoys broad support across all major web browsers, including Microsoft Internet Explorer versions 5 and above, Mozilla Firefox versions 1.0 and beyond, Opera versions 7.6 and above, and Apple Safari versions 1.2 and higher.
[src:jquery/api-eventtarget] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:jquery/api-eventtarget] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:jquery/api-eventtarget] The **`EventTarget`** interface is implemented by objects that can receive events and may have listeners for them.
[src:jquery/api-eventtarget] In other words, any target of events implements the three methods associated with this interface.
[src:jquery/api-eventtarget] `Element`, and its children, as well as `Document` and `Window`, are the most common event targets, but other objects can be event targets, too.
[src:jquery/api-eventtarget] For example `IDBRequest`, `AudioNode`, and `AudioContext` are also event targets.
[src:jquery/api-eventtarget] Many event targets (including elements, documents, and windows) also support registering event handlers via `onevent` properties and attributes.
[src:jquery/api-eventtarget] Creates a new `EventTarget` object instance.
[src:jquery/api-eventtarget] Registers an event handler of a specific event type on the `EventTarget`.
[src:jquery/api-eventtarget] Removes an event listener from the `EventTarget`.
[src:jquery/api-eventtarget] Dispatches an event to this `EventTarget`.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] The **Document Object Model** (**DOM**) connects web pages to scripts or programming languages by representing the structure of a document—such as the HTML representing a web page—in memory.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] Usually it refers to JavaScript, even though modeling HTML, SVG, or XML documents as objects are not part of the core JavaScript language.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] The DOM represents a document with a logical tree.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] Each branch of the tree ends in a node, and each node contains objects.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] DOM methods allow programmatic access to the tree.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] With them, you can change the document's structure, style, or content.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] Nodes can also have event handlers attached to them.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] Once an event is triggered, the event handlers get executed.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] The Document Object Model (DOM) is a programming interface for web documents.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] It represents the page so that programs can change the document structure, style, and content.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] The DOM represents the document as nodes and objects; that way, programming languages can interact with the page.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] A web page is a document that can be either displayed in the browser window or as the HTML source.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] In both cases, it is the same document but the Document Object Model (DOM) representation allows it to be manipulated.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] As an object-oriented representation of the web page, it can be modified with a scripting language such as JavaScript.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] All of the properties, methods, and events available for manipulating and creating web pages are organized into objects.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] For example, the `document` object that represents the document itself, any `table` objects that implement the `HTMLTableElement` DOM interface for accessing HTML tables, and so forth, are all objects.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] The DOM is built using multiple APIs that work together.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] The core DOM defines the entities describing any document and the objects within it.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] This is expanded upon as needed by other APIs that add new features and capabilities to the DOM.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] For example, the HTML DOM API adds support for representing HTML documents to the core DOM, and the SVG API adds support for representing SVG documents.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] A **DOM tree** is a tree structure whose nodes represent an HTML or XML document's contents.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] Each HTML or XML document has a DOM tree representation.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] Although the above tree is similar to the above document's DOM tree, they're not identical, as the actual DOM tree preserves whitespace.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] When a web browser parses an HTML document, it builds a DOM tree and then uses it to display the document.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] The previous short example, like nearly all examples, is JavaScript.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] That is to say, it is *written* in JavaScript, but *uses* the DOM to access the document and its elements.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] The DOM is not a programming language, but without it, the JavaScript language wouldn't have any model or notion of web pages, HTML documents, SVG documents, and their component parts.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] The document as a whole, the head, tables within the document, table headers, text within the table cells, and all other elements in a document are parts of the document object model for that document.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] They can all be accessed and manipulated using the DOM and a scripting language like JavaScript.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] The DOM is not part of the JavaScript language, but is instead a Web API used to build websites.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] JavaScript can also be used in other contexts.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] For example, Node.js runs JavaScript programs on a computer, but provides a different set of APIs, and the DOM API is not a core part of the Node.js runtime.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] The DOM was designed to be independent of any particular programming language, making the structural representation of the document available from a single, consistent API.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] For more information on what technologies are involved in writing JavaScript on the web, see JavaScript technologies overview.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] You don't have to do anything special to begin using the DOM.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] You use the API directly in JavaScript from within what is called a *script*, a program run by a browser.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] When you create a script, whether inline in a `<script>` element or included in the web page, you can immediately begin using the API for the `document` or `window` objects to manipulate the document itself, or any of the various elements in the web page (the descendant elements of the document).
[src:jquery/document-object-model] As it is generally not recommended to mix the structure of the page (written in HTML) and manipulation of the DOM (written in JavaScript), the JavaScript parts will be grouped together here, and separated from the HTML.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] This guide is about the objects and the actual *things* you can use to manipulate the DOM hierarchy.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] There are many points where understanding how these work can be confusing.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] For example, the object representing the HTML `form` element gets its `name` property from the `HTMLFormElement` interface but its `className` property from the `HTMLElement` interface.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] In both cases, the property you want is in that form object.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] But the relationship between objects and the interfaces that they implement in the DOM can be confusing, and so this section attempts to say a little something about the actual interfaces in the DOM specification and how they are made available.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] Many objects implement several different interfaces.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] The table object, for example, implements a specialized `HTMLTableElement` interface, which includes such methods as `createCaption` and `insertRow`.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] But since it's also an HTML element, `table` implements the `Element` interface described in the DOM `Element` Reference chapter.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] And finally, since an HTML element is also, as far as the DOM is concerned, a node in the tree of nodes that make up the object model for an HTML or XML page, the table object also implements the more basic `Node` interface, from which `Element` derives.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] When you get a reference to a `table` object, as in the following example, you routinely use all three of these interfaces interchangeably on the object, perhaps without knowing it.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] This page tries to describe the various objects and types in simple terms.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] But there are a number of different data types being passed around the API that you should be aware of.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] The following table briefly describes these data types.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] There are also some common terminology considerations to keep in mind.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] It's common to refer to any `Attr` node as an `attribute`, for example, and to refer to an array of DOM nodes as a `nodeList`.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] You'll find these terms and others to be introduced and used throughout the documentation.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] The `document` and `window` objects are the objects whose interfaces you generally use most often in DOM programming.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] In simple terms, the `window` object represents something like the browser, and the `document` object is the root of the document itself.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] `Element` inherits from the generic `Node` interface, and together these two interfaces provide many of the methods and properties you use on individual elements.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] These elements may also have specific interfaces for dealing with the kind of data those elements hold, as in the `table` object example in the previous section.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] The Document Object Model has been highly simplified.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] To achieve this, the following interfaces in the different DOM level 3 or earlier specifications have been removed.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] They are no longer available to web developers.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] A document containing HTML is described using the `Document` interface, which is extended by the HTML specification to include various HTML-specific features.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] In particular, the `Element` interface is enhanced to become `HTMLElement` and various subclasses, each representing one of (or a family of closely related) elements.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] The HTML DOM API provides access to various browser features such as tabs and windows, CSS styles and stylesheets, browser history, etc.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] These interfaces are discussed further in the HTML DOM API documentation.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] Similarly, a document containing SVG is also described using the `Document` interface, which is extended by the SVG specification to include various SVG-specific features.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] In particular, the `Element` interface is enhanced to become `SVGElement` and various subclasses, each representing an element or a family of closely related elements.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] These interfaces are discussed further in the SVG API documentation.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] This example uses a `<div>` element containing a `<textarea>` and two `<button>` elements.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] When the user clicks the first button we set some text in the `<textarea>`.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] When the user clicks the second button we clear the text.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] This example uses a `<div>` element containing a `<div>` and two `<button>` elements.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] When the user clicks the first button we create a new element and add it as a child of the `<div>`.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] When the user clicks the second button we remove the child element.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] Suppose the author wants to change the header of the document in What is a DOM tree? and write two paragraphs instead of one.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] You can create the tree in What is a DOM tree? entirely in JavaScript too.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] This example demonstrates how events fire and are handled in the DOM in a very simple way.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] When the BODY of this HTML document loads, an event listener is registered with the top row of the TABLE.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] The event listener handles the event by executing the function stopEvent, which changes the value in the bottom cell of the table.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] However, stopEvent also calls an event object method, `event.stopPropagation`, which keeps the event from bubbling any further up into the DOM.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] Note that the table itself has an `onclick` event handler that ought to display a message when the table is clicked.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] But the stopEvent method has stopped propagation, and so after the data in the table is updated, the event phase is effectively ended, and an alert box is displayed to confirm this.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] This example uses DOM methods to display all the properties of the `click` event object and their values in a table.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] It also shows a useful technique of using a `for...in` loop to iterate over the properties of an object to get their values.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] The properties of event objects differs greatly between browsers, the WHATWG DOM Standard lists the standard properties, however many browsers have extended these greatly.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] Put the following code into a blank text file and load it into a variety of browsers, you'll be surprised at the different number and names of properties.
[src:jquery/document-object-model] You might also like to add some elements in the page and call this function from different event handlers.
[src:jquery/javascript-library] A **JavaScript library** is a library of pre-written JavaScript code that allows for easier development of JavaScript-based applications, especially for AJAX and other web-centric technologies.
[src:jquery/javascript-library] They can be included in a website by embedding it directly in the HTML via a script tag.
[src:jquery/javascript-library] With the expanded demands for JavaScript, an easier means for programmers to develop such dynamic interfaces was needed.
[src:jquery/javascript-library] Thus, JavaScript libraries and JavaScript widget libraries were developed, allowing for developers to concentrate more upon more distinctive applications of Ajax.
[src:jquery/javascript-library] This has led to other companies and groups, such as Microsoft and Yahoo! developing their own JavaScript-based user interface libraries, which find their way into the web applications developed by these companies.
[src:jquery/javascript-library] Some JavaScript libraries allow for easier integration of JavaScript with other web development technologies, such as CSS, PHP, Ruby, and Java, while others provide utilities, often in the form of JavaScript functions, to make repetitive and complex tasks less taxing.
[src:jquery/javascript-library] Many libraries include code to detect differences between runtime environments and remove the need for applications to allow for such inconsistencies.
[src:jquery/javascript-library] Almost all JavaScript libraries are released under either a permissive or copyleft license to ensure license-free distribution, usage, and modification.
[src:jquery/javascript-library] Some JavaScript libraries, such as Angular, are classified as frameworks since they exhibit full-stack capabilities and properties not found in general JavaScript libraries.
[src:jquery/javascript-library] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:jquery/javascript-library] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:jquery/javascript-library] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:jquery/javascript-library] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:jquery/javascript-library] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:jquery/javascript-library] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:jquery/javascript-library] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:jquery/javascript-library] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:jquery/javascript-library] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:jquery/javascript-library] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:jquery/javascript-library] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:jquery/javascript-library] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:jquery/javascript-library] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:jquery/javascript-library] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:jquery/javascript-library] All npm packages are JavaScript libraries, but not all libraries are packages.
[src:jquery/javascript-library] Npm serves as a package manager for packages used in Node.js runtimes.
[src:jquery/javascript-library] However, some npm packages offer CDN support for use of the library in both Node.js runtimes as well as the browser.
[src:jquery/jquery] jQuery's syntax is designed to make it easier to navigate a document, select DOM elements, create animations, handle events, and develop Ajax applications. jQuery also provides capabilities for developers to create plug-ins on top of the JavaScript library.
[src:jquery/jquery] This enables developers to create abstractions for low-level interaction and animation, advanced effects and high-level, theme-able widgets.
[src:jquery/jquery] The modular approach to the jQuery library allows the creation of powerful dynamic web pages and Web applications.
[src:jquery/jquery] The set of jQuery core features—DOM element selections, traversal, and manipulation—enabled by its *selector engine* (named "Sizzle" from v1.3), created a new "programming style", fusing algorithms and DOM data structures.
[src:jquery/jquery] This style influenced the architecture of other JavaScript frameworks like YUI v3 and Dojo, later stimulating the creation of the standard *Selectors API*.
[src:jquery/jquery] Microsoft and Nokia bundle jQuery on their platforms.
[src:jquery/jquery] Microsoft includes it with Visual Studio for use within Microsoft's ASP.NET AJAX and ASP.NET MVC frameworks while Nokia has integrated it into the Web Run-Time widget development platform.
[src:jquery/jquery] jQuery, at its core, is a Document Object Model (DOM) manipulation library.
[src:jquery/jquery] The DOM is a tree-structure representation of all the elements of a Web page. jQuery simplifies the syntax for finding, selecting, and manipulating these DOM elements.
[src:jquery/jquery] For example, jQuery can be used for finding an element in the document with a certain property (e.g. all elements with the `h1` tag), changing one or more of its attributes (e.g.
[src:jquery/jquery] `color`, `visibility`), or making it respond to an event (e.g. a mouse click).
[src:jquery/jquery] jQuery also provides a paradigm for event handling that goes beyond basic DOM element selection and manipulation.
[src:jquery/jquery] The event assignment and the event callback function definition are done in a single step in a single location in the code. jQuery also aims to incorporate other highly used JavaScript functionality (e.g. fade ins and fade outs when hiding elements, animations by manipulating CSS properties).
[src:jquery/jquery] jQuery was originally created in January 2006 at BarCamp NYC by John Resig, influenced by Dean Edwards' earlier cssQuery library.
[src:jquery/jquery] It is currently maintained by a team of developers led by Timmy Willison (with the jQuery selector engine, Sizzle, being led by Richard Gibson).
[src:jquery/jquery] jQuery was originally licensed under the CC BY-SA 2.5, and relicensed to the MIT License in 2006.
[src:jquery/jquery] At the end of 2006, it was dual-licensed under GPL and MIT licenses.
[src:jquery/jquery] As this led to some confusion, in 2012 the GPL was dropped and is now only licensed under the MIT license.
[src:jquery/jquery] jQuery 3.0 and newer supports "current−1 versions" (meaning the current stable version of the browser and the version that preceded it) of Firefox (and ESR), Chrome, Safari, and Edge as well as Internet Explorer 9 and newer.
[src:jquery/jquery] On mobile it supports iOS 7 and newer, and Android 4.0 and newer.
[src:jquery/jquery] The jQuery library is typically distributed as a single JavaScript file that defines all its interfaces, including DOM, Events, and Ajax functions.
[src:jquery/jquery] It can be included within a Web page by linking to a local copy or by linking to one of the many copies available from public servers. jQuery has a content delivery network (CDN) hosted by MaxCDN.
[src:jquery/jquery] Google in Google Hosted Libraries service and Microsoft host the library as well.
[src:jquery/jquery] jQuery provides two kinds of functions, static utility functions and jQuery object methods.
[src:jquery/jquery] Both are accessed through jQuery's main identifier: `jQuery`.
[src:jquery/jquery] All functions can be accessed through either of these two names.
[src:jquery/jquery] The `jQuery` function is a factory for creating a jQuery object that represents one or more DOM nodes. jQuery objects have methods to manipulate these nodes.
[src:jquery/jquery] These methods (sometimes called *commands)*, are *chainable* as each method also returns a jQuery object.
[src:jquery/jquery] Access to and manipulation of multiple DOM nodes in jQuery typically begins with calling the `$` function with a CSS selector string.
[src:jquery/jquery] This returns a jQuery object referencing all the matching elements in the HTML page.
[src:jquery/jquery] `$("div.test")`, for example, returns a jQuery object with all the `div` elements that have the class `test`.
[src:jquery/jquery] This node set can be manipulated by calling methods on the returned jQuery object.
[src:jquery/jquery] These are utility functions and do not directly act upon a jQuery object.
[src:jquery/jquery] They are accessed as static methods on the jQuery or $ identifier.
[src:jquery/jquery] For example, `$.ajax()` is a static method.
[src:jquery/jquery] jQuery provides a `$.noConflict()` function, which relinquishes control of the `$` name.
[src:jquery/jquery] This is useful if jQuery is used on a Web page also linking another library that demands the `$` symbol as its identifier.
[src:jquery/jquery] In no-conflict mode, developers can use `jQuery` as a replacement for `$` without losing functionality.
[src:jquery/jquery] Typically, jQuery is used by putting initialization code and event handling functions in `$(*handler*)`.
[src:jquery/jquery] This is triggered by jQuery when the browser has finished constructing the DOM for the current Web page.
[src:jquery/jquery] Historically, `$(document).ready(callback)` has been the de facto idiom for running code after the DOM is ready.
[src:jquery/jquery] However, since jQuery 3.0, developers are encouraged to use the much shorter `$(handler)` signature instead.
[src:jquery/jquery] This line finds all `div` elements with class attribute `test` , then registers an event handler on each element for the "click" event, then adds the class attribute `foo` to each element.
[src:jquery/jquery] Certain jQuery object methods retrieve specific values (instead of modifying a state).
[src:jquery/jquery] An example of this is the `val()` method, which returns the current value of a text input element.
[src:jquery/jquery] In these cases, a statement such as `$('#user-email').val()` cannot be used for chaining as the return value does not reference a jQuery object.
[src:jquery/jquery] Besides accessing existing DOM nodes through jQuery, it is also possible to create new DOM nodes, if the string passed as the argument to `$()` factory looks like HTML.
[src:jquery/jquery] It is possible to make Ajax requests (with cross-browser support) with `$.ajax()` to load and manipulate remote data.
[src:jquery/jquery] This example posts the data `name=John` and `location=Boston` to `/process/submit.php` on the server.
[src:jquery/jquery] When this request finishes the success function is called to alert the user.
[src:jquery/jquery] If the request fails it will alert the user to the failure, the status of the request, and the specific error.
[src:jquery/jquery] The above example uses the `.then()` and `.catch()` methods to register callbacks that run when the response has completed.
[src:jquery/jquery] These promise callbacks must be used due to the asynchronous nature of Ajax requests.
[src:jquery/jquery] jQuery's architecture allows developers to create plug-in code to extend its function.
[src:jquery/jquery] There are thousands of jQuery plug-ins available on the Web that cover a range of functions, such as Ajax helpers, Web services, datagrids, dynamic lists, XML and XSLT tools, drag and drop, events, cookie handling, and modal windows.
[src:jquery/jquery] An important source of jQuery plug-ins is the plugins sub-domain of the jQuery Project website.
[src:jquery/jquery] The plugins in this subdomain, however, were accidentally deleted in December 2011 in an attempt to rid the site of spam.
[src:jquery/jquery] The new site is a GitHub-hosted repository, which required developers to resubmit their plugins and to conform to new submission requirements. jQuery provides a "Learning Center" that can help users understand JavaScript and get started developing jQuery plugins.
[src:jquery/jquery] Additionally, for those looking to convert jQuery plugins or code to vanilla JavaScript, tools like the [jQuery to JavaScript Converter](https://codentools.com/jquery-convert-javascript) can be very helpful in automating part of the transition and reducing reliance on jQuery.
[src:jquery/jquery] QUnit is a test automation framework used to test the jQuery project.
[src:jquery/jquery] The jQuery team developed it as an in-house unit testing library.
[src:jquery/jquery] The jQuery team uses it to test its code and plugins, but it can test any generic JavaScript code, including server-side JavaScript code.
[src:jquery/jquery] As of 2011, the jQuery Testing Team uses QUnit with TestSwarm to test each jQuery codebase release.
[src:jquery/jquery] As cross-browser compatibility is no longer as much of an issue, most of jQuery can nowadays be replaced with modern web standards, without losing much convenience.
[src:jquery/jquery] Partly due to this, GitHub removed jQuery from its pages in 2018.
